snippet.textDisplay: There is a much easier and safer way. I just take a photo of the left and the right halve of the keyboard, unplug all keycaps, put them in a larger piece of old sock or shirt, close it with a zip-tie and throw that little bundle (just it) in the washing machine on the lowest temperature, without tumbling and with liquid washing soap (the kind for wool). This program takes 15 minutes. In those 15 minutes, i clean the keyboard with papertowels and cotton swabs with alcohol, until its spotless. Then i rinse the satchel in warm water to get the soap out and i then take a regular towel, form a satchel with my right hand (i.e. close the thing with my hands), shake it, punch it lightly and after 30 seconds or so, they a dry enough. Take your pictures as a reference and reassemble. Tadaa, buttons spotless, keyboard looks like new and the circuits and electronics haven't been submerged in water and you don´t loose your warranty AND don´t have to wait a week for it to dry. Cheers from Germany! >:)

snippet.textDisplay:
Just want to point out that soap does not sterilise or disinfect. Soap is used as part of cleaning which is a mechanical operation related to friction. The primary function of soap is to make a surface slippery so dirt can be removed easier.

Dishwasher tablets contain more than just soap, they also contain shiners which are designed to leave a residue that makes glass appear clearer and shinier.

Would you like to know more?

snippet.textDisplay:
I did this before, twice, with my only keyboard (which I'm typing on right now). After you clean it and thoroughly dry it, you must disassemble the whole keyboard and depending on your type, clean all the plastic layers in between (mine had 3 layers). It must be perfectly dry between the layers or else your keyboard wont work (more precisely, the key presses wont register correctly if theres even the slightest bit of moisture in between some layer).

Ofcourse this is just a basic Logitech K120 keyboard, with advanced gaming keyboards I wouldn't do it as there's more actual hardware involved that could break upon exposure to water.

snippet.textDisplay: Dishwashing your keyboard is "fine" so long as you allow it to drip dry for long enough. However, tap water is not the same across the globe, and the cleanliness of your dishwasher and plumbing will vary too. In my experience with dishwashing mechanical keyboards, even though they are still alive many years later, the MX Browns in my samples have turned to absolute mush. Dishwashing your keycaps is for the most part safe, but I can not wholeheartedly recommend throwing the entire board in there unless you're ready to introduce all sorts of contaminants to your switches and pcb.

snippet.textDisplay:
Wouldn't the springs in the mechanical key switches rust? I tried washing my Cherry keyboard once in water a very long time ago. The result was that 3-4 keys started to stick (they don't seem to bounce back as well as they should).


Since then I've always just covered my keyboard if I absoultely want to be eating or drinking in front of my PC. Hair and dust still build up over time, but they are trivial to clean with a soft brush after taking off the key caps. The best way to clean it is always just to keep it clean.
